Introduction¶

Reinforcement Learning¶

  • Reinforcement learning differs from other supervised methods in that you have an interactive-goal seeking ML agent.
  • All reinforcement learning agents have explicit goals, can sense aspects of their environments, and can choose actions to influence their environments.

Sutton, Richard S., and Andrew G. Barto. Reinforcement learning: An introduction. MIT press, 2018.

  • I paraphrase from the textbook

Elements of Reinforcement Learning¶

  • Agent
  • Agent Our ML programming doing our tasks.
  • It will be comprised of several things below.
  • Environment

The think that the agent interacts with.

  • Policy
    • learning agent’s way of behaving at a given time
  • Policy
    • Roughly speaking, a policy is a mapping from perceived states of the environment to actions to be taken when in those states.
    • It can be a function or a look up table
      • They can even be stochastic.
    • There can also be multiple policies
      • Multiple policies end up being multiple models
    • core of a reinforcement learning agent in that it alone is sufficient to determine behavior.
  • Reward signal
    • the goal in a reinforcement learning problem
  • Reward Signal
    • On each time step, the environment sends to the reinforcement learning agent a single number, a reward.
      • The agent’s sole objective is to maximize the total reward it receives over the long run.
      • The reward encodes good and bad events for the agent.
      • These rewards are immidate
        • In a biological system, pleasure or pain.
    • The reward sent to the agent at any time depends on the agent’s current action and the current state of the agent’s environment.
    • the agent's actions are influence by the reward signal.
    • The reward signal is the primary basis for altering the policy.
    • In general, reward signals may be stochastic functions of the state of the environment and the actions taken.
  • Value Function
    • total amount of reward an agent can expect to gather in the future, starting from that state
  • Value Function
    • the reward signal indicates what is good in an immediate sense, a value function specifies what is good in the long run.
      • It's an attempt at encoding long term planning
    • values indicate the long-term desirability of states after taking into account the states that are likely to follow, and the rewards available in those states.
      • in constrast to rewards determine the immediate, intrinsic desirability of environmental states,
      • For example, a state might always yield a low immediate reward but still have a high value because it is regularly followed by other states that yield high rewards.
      • Or the reverse could be true.
  • Internal Model of Environment
  • Internal Model of Environment
    • Models are used for planning
      • any way of deciding on a course of action by considering possible future situations before they are actually experienced.
    • We will be talking about model-free based methods that are explicitly trial-and-error learners.

The Environment¶

Arcade Learning Environment¶

  • Atari 2600 games are well suited for evaluating general competency in AI agents for three main reasons:
    1. they are varied enough to provide multiple different tasks
    2. they are interesting and challenging for humans
    3. they are free of experimenter’s bias, having been developed by an independent party
  • Agents are expected to perform well in as many games as possible making minimal assumptions about the domain at hand and without the use of game-specific information
  • https://github.com/mgbellemare/Arcade-Learning-Environment
  • M. G. Bellemare, Y. Naddaf, J. Veness and M. Bowling. The Arcade Learning Environment: An Evaluation Platform for General Agents, Journal of Artificial Intelligence Research, Volume 47, pages 253-279, 2013.
  • Machado, Marlos C., et al. "Revisiting the arcade learning environment: Evaluation protocols and open problems for general agents." Journal of Artificial Intelligence Research 61 (2018): 523-562.
  • This paper out lines why this game environment is suitable for evaluating AI agents.
  • They also provide source code in python for any hobbiest or researcher to have an ML model interact with the environment fairly easily.

Previous Work¶

Q Learning¶

  • A model free RL algorithm to learn the value of an action at a particular state.
  • Q value or Quality Value
  • This will be basis of the value function we will be talking about.

Bellman Equation¶

$$ Q^{new}(s_{t},a_{t}) \leftarrow \underbrace{Q(s_{t},a_{t})}_{\text{old value}} + \underbrace{\alpha}_{\text{learning rate}} \cdot \overbrace{\bigg( \underbrace{\underbrace{r_{t}}_{\text{reward}} + \underbrace{\gamma}_{\text{discount factor}} \cdot \underbrace{\max_{a}Q(s_{t+1}, a)}_{\text{estimate of optimal future value}}}_{\text{new value (temporal difference target)}} - \underbrace{Q(s_{t},a_{t})}_{\text{old value}} \bigg) }^{\text{temporal difference}} $$
  • $s_{t+1}=T\left(s_{t},a_{t}\right)$
  • gamma is the discount factor, which controls the importance of long term rewards in comparision to the immediate one.
  • The Q Value from state s and selecting action a, is the immediate reward, r(s,a), plus the highest Q value resulting in the new state, $s^{\prime}$ which is a resulting of taking action a.
  • (1-alpha) Q(s_t,a_t)
    • the current value weighted by the learning rate. Values of the learning rate near to 1 make the changes in Q more rapid.
  • alpha r_t
    • the reward r_t obtaint if action a_t is taken in state s_t
  • \alpha gamma max{a} Q(s{t+1},a)
    • the maximum reward that can be obtained from state s_{t+1}
  • You can view that as a dynamic programming problem.

Deep Q Network (DQN)¶

  • It's not feasible to keep track of all the states
  • Approximate the $Q$ values with a neural network
    • More specifically deep convolutional neural network
  • In 2015 they published to Nature, and shook up the ML world.
  • in 49 ATari games using the same algorithm, network architecture and hyperparameters, was able to surpass the performance of all previous algorithms and achieve a level comparable to that of a professional human games tester.

Mnih, Volodymyr, et al. "Human-level control through deep reinforcement learning." nature 518.7540 (2015): 529-533.

  • Here you can see how one would use a Neural Network to play a video game
  • this forward calculation has to happen every frame
  • most old console games ran at 60 FPS
  • most modern console games run at either 30 or 60 FPS

Recurrent Replay Distributed DQN (R2D2)¶

  • combining a neural network model with short-term memory and off-policy learning and distributed training to achieving a very strong average performance
    • Kapturowski, Steven, et al. "Recurrent experience replay in distributed reinforcement learning." International conference on learning representations. 2018.
  • 2018

Distributed Networks¶

Decouples the data collection and the learning process

  • Multiple actors learning from independent copies of the environment and send traning data back to a centeral location
  • A learning algorithm can then sample the traning data and learn form it
  • Ong, Hao Yi, Kevin Chavez, and Augustus Hong. "Distributed deep Q-learning." arXiv preprint arXiv:1508.04186 (2015).
  • Introduced soon after DQN in 2015 and key to the R2D2 Agent

Distributed Networks Visualization¶

  • Badia, Adrià Puigdomènech, et al. "Agent57: Outperforming the atari human benchmark." International Conference on Machine Learning. PMLR, 2020.
  • This is the what is used for the agent, Agent57, described in this paper
    • From Deep Blue
  • This replay buffer is similar to how a person might recall memories to better learn from them

Short Term Memory¶

  • Recurrent Neural Network
  • Hochreiter, Sepp, and Jürgen Schmidhuber. "Long short-term memory." Neural computation 9.8 (1997): 1735-1780.
  • For the R2D2 Agent
    • Implemented with hidden variables in a network that pass them selves forward to the next compute step.
    • The details of those hidden variables and how they influence the network as a whole is a much greater topic.

R2D2 Architecture¶

  • Badia, Adrià Puigdomènech, et al. "Never give up: Learning directed exploration strategies." arXiv preprint arXiv:2002.06038 (2020).
  • you can see the state input, x_t, in to a convolutional network
  • then into a long-short term network with the past action, a_{t-1}, the the extrinsic/intrinsic rewards and exploration rate beta.
    • and the LSTM has ourput than is returned to itself.
  • the LSTM output is then passed to the normal Reinforment Learning Network

Never Give Up (NGU)¶

  • Exploration
  • epsilon_l-greedy
    • this family of techniques do not scale well to hard exploration problems: in the absence of rewards, they require a prohibitive amount of time to explore large state-action spaces, as they rely on undirected random action choices to discover unseen states.
  • Episodic Memory
    • $r_t^{\text{intrinsic}} = r_t^{\text{episodic}} \cdot \min\left(\max\left(\alpha_t, 1\right), L\right)$
      • Long-term novelty provided by $\alpha_{t}$
      • $L$, the maximum reward scaling, emprically $L$ chosen to be 5
  • Badia, Adrià Puigdomènech, et al. "Never give up: Learning directed exploration strategies." arXiv preprint arXiv:2002.06038 (2020).
  • r_{t}^{intrinsic}
    • intrinsic reward
  • r_{t}^{episodic}
    • per-episode novelty reward
    • encourage the agent to explore within an episode
    • Short Term Novelty
      • This enables NGU to detect when new parts of a game are encountered, so the agent can explore these newer parts of the game in case they yield reward.
  • Long Term Novelty
    • signal when a previously unseen state is encountered in the agent's lifetime
      • This is done by comparing against a density of states seen so far in training.
        • that is, it's adjusted by how often the agent has seen a state similar to the current one relative to states seen overall.
        • When the density is high (indicating that the state is familiar), the long term novelty reward is low, and vice versa.
        • When all the states are familiar, the agent resorts to an undirected exploration strategy.

Contribution of this paper¶

Agent57¶

== Blank Notes ==

  • Meta-controller: learning to balance exploration with exploitation
    • Agent57 is built on the following observation:
      • what if an agent can learn when its better to exploit, and when its better to explore?
    • Two Important Consequences
      • allocate more of the capacity of the network to policies that are most relevant for the task at hand
      • provide a natural way of choosing the best policy in the family to use at evaluation time
  • an adaptive mechanism to select which of the policies to prioritize throughout the training process. This allows the agent to control the exploration/exploitation trade-off by dedicating more resources to one or the other.
  • The core idea of NGU is to jointly train a family of policies with different degrees of exploratory behaviour using a single network architecture.
    • In this way, training these exploratory policies plays the role of a set of auxiliary tasks that can help train the shared architecture even in the absence of extrinsic rewards.
    • A major limitation of this approach is that all policies are trained equally, regardless of their contribution to the learning progress.
  • This meta-controller that can adaptively select which policies to use both at training and evaluation time.

This carries two important consequences.

1) we can allocate more of the capacity of the network to better represent the state-action value function of the policies that are most relevant for the task at hand.

2) this mechanism also provides a natural way of choosing the best policy in the family to use at evaluation time.

- Considering a wide range of values of gamma_{j} with beta_{j} ~ 0, provides a way of automatically adjusting the discount factor on a per-task basis.

This significantly increases the generality of the approach.

  • A new parameterization of the state-action value function that decomposes the contributions of the intrinsic and extrinsic rewards.
    • $Q\left(x,a,j; \theta\right) = Q\left(x,a,j; \theta^{\text{extrinsic}}\right) + \beta_{j}Q\left(x,a,j; \theta^{\text{intrinsic}}\right)$
      • $\theta^{\text{extrinsic}}$ and $\theta^{\text{intrinsic}}$ separately parameterize two neural networks with identical architecture.
        • Appendix B of the Agent 57 paper goes through the Extrinsic-Intrinsic Decomposition
  • two different neural networks are used to approximate each one of these state-action values
    • we allow each network to adapt to the scale and variance associated with their corresponding reward, and we also allow for the associated optimizer state to be separated for intrinsic and extrinsic state-action value functions.
      • Each network is searching for a differenct optimal state that is associated to either the intrinsic and extrinsic state-action value function.
  • \beta_{j}
    • the exploration rates are parameters that control the degree of exploration
      • Higher values will encorage exploratory polices and smaller values will encorage exploitative policies.
    • j is an index for different time scales
  • Note that each Q_{rj}^{*} have it's own assosiated discount factor \gamma{j} for the purposes of learning long-term credit assignment.
    • Appendix B of the Agent 57 paper goes through the Extrinsic-Intrinsic Decomposition

Agent57 Architecture¶

  • Here you can see the two networks for the intrinsic and extrinsic reward.
  • You see that exploration rate, \beta_{j}
  • the h transformation you see there are there for generality
    • they are used to calculate a transformed bellman operator.
    • though they found the identity function to work for their experinments
    • they go over the derivation of a specific h in Appendix A of the Agent57 paper
    • also in Appendix H, they go over some empirical evidence showing it doesn't play an important role.
